```

Now look at that! The binaryTreeRecursionReplacer looks almost like our map function from the beginning, but instead of applying the provided function (replacer) to the value stored in a node, the function is applied to the recursive fields (left and right). So we can think of it as an alternative completly different way of mapping over the tree node.

Also look at the binaryTreeReduce function now. It is really short now! The handling of all the cases has been moved into the binaryTreeRecursionReplacer function. What is left in binaryTreeReduce is the pure recursion. This is our codified recursion scheme!

Lets put everything back together:

## RecursiveReduction

```elixir
defmodule SparseTreeRecursionMap do
  # define a recursive structure in terms of a mapping
  # over the recursive fields
  def mapRecur(tree, fun) do
    case tree do
      :empty ->
        :empty

      {:leaf, value} ->
        {:leaf, value}

      {:inner, inner_value, left, right} ->
        {
          :inner,
          inner_value,
          fun.(left),
          fun.(right)
        }
    end
  end
end

# The catamorphism
defmodule RecursiveReduction do
  # the reduction can be applied to any
  # recursive structure via the recursive mapping function_exported
  def reduce(data, mapRecur, handleCases) do
    data
    |> mapRecur.(fn
      child -> reduce(child, mapRecur, handleCases)
    end)
    |> handleCases.()
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

