Besides the Catamorphism that we discovered step by step on our own, there are many more recursion schemes, that have already been discovered, named and categorized.

Lets take a look at two of them: Anamorphism and Hylomorphism

## Anamorphism and Hylomorphism

```elixir
defmodule Anamorphism do
  # the oppsoite of cata:
  # take a single seed value and expand it into a recursive structure
  # eg turn 5 into [1,2,3,4,5]
  def ana(seed, mapRecur, handleCases) do
    seed
    |> handleCases.()
    |> mapRecur.(fn
      child -> ana(child, mapRecur, handleCases)
    end)
  end
end

defmodule Hylomorphism do
  # composition of cata and ana:
  # takes a single seed, turns it into a recursive structure
  # and then reduce this structure back into a value
  def hylo(seed, mapRecur, coalgebra, algebra) do
    seed
    |> coalgebra.()
    |> mapRecur.(fn
      child -> hylo(child, mapRecur, coalgebra, algebra)
    end)
    |> algebra.()
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

## Co-Algebras

The common name for `handleCases` in the context of cata is *Algebra* and in the context of `ana` it is called *CoAlgebra*.

We can define some co algebras for our `LinkedListStructure`

```elixir
defmodule LinkedListStructure.CoAlgebras do
  # coundown takes a single value and produces a list like structure
  # the result is not a proper list itself, but a const pair [a | b]
  # with a being a value to put into a list and b the value for FROM WHICH
  # the tail shall be generated.

  # returning [5 | 4] results in a list containing the value 5 as head and the list
  # generated from the seed 4 as tail
  # ana(5, countdown) will generate the list [5,4,3,2,1]
  def countdown(num) do
    case num do
      0 -> []
      n -> [n | n - 1]
    end
  end

  # ana(5, upto) will generate the list [1,2,3,4]
  def upto(goal) do
    fn
      ^goal -> []
      n -> [n | n + 1]
    end
  end

  # ana(5, upto) will generate the list [1,2,3,4,5]
  def upto_inclusive(goal) do
    fn
      :stop -> []
      ^goal -> [goal | :stop]
      n -> [n | n + 1]
    end
  end

  # ana(6, repeat(7)) will generate the list [7,7,7,7,7,7]
  def repeat(constant) do
    fn
      0 -> []
      n -> [constant | n - 1]
    end
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

Now we can use the anamorphism together with our co-algebras to generate some lists.

